00:32:10,960 --> 00:32:15,280
I think one thing that's been counterintuitive 
for us, [inaudible 00:32:14] added a little bit  

370
00:32:15,280 --> 00:32:20,240
before, but is, we definitely didn't expect 
to be doing any of our own model development  

371
00:32:20,240 --> 00:32:25,040
when we started. As mentioned, when we got into 
this, there were companies that were immediately  

372
00:32:25,040 --> 00:32:31,920
from the get-go going and just focusing on 
training model from scratch. And we had done  

373
00:32:31,920 --> 00:32:36,720
the calculation for what it to train before, and 
just knew that that was not [inaudible 00:32:36]  

374
00:32:36,720 --> 00:32:42,800
going to be able to do. And also felt a bit 
like focusing one's attention in the wrong area,  

375
00:32:42,800 --> 00:32:46,400
because there were lots of amazing models 
out there, and why develop all this work  

376
00:32:46,400 --> 00:32:50,960
to replicate what other players had done. 
Especially on the pre-training side of things,  

377
00:32:50,960 --> 00:32:55,920
taking a neural network that knows nothing, 
and then teaching it the whole internet. 

378
00:32:55,920 --> 00:33:01,680
And so we thought we weren't going to be doing 
that at all, and it seems clear to us from the  

379
00:33:01,680 --> 00:33:06,080
start that the existing models, there were lots 
of things that they could be doing for us that  

380
00:33:06,080 --> 00:33:10,000
they weren't doing, because there wasn't the 
right tool built for them. In fact though,  

381
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:16,240
we do a ton of model development, and internally, 
it's a big focus for us on the hiring front,  

382
00:33:16,240 --> 00:33:20,960
and have assembled a fantastic team there.
And it's also been a big win on the product  

383
00:33:20,960 --> 00:33:25,920
quality side of things for us. And at this 
point, every magic moment in Cursor involves  

384
00:33:25,920 --> 00:33:34,320
a custom model in some way. So that was definitely 
counterintuitive, and surprising, and it's been a  

385
00:33:34,320 --> 00:33:38,640
gradual thing, where there was an initial use case 
for training our own model, where it really didn't  

386
00:33:38,640 --> 00:33:42,160
make sense to use any of the biggest foundation 
models. That was incredibly successful, moved  

387
00:33:42,160 --> 00:33:50,160
to another use case that worked really well, and 
had been going from there. And one of the helpful  

388
00:33:50,160 --> 00:33:55,520
things in doing this sort of model development 
is picking your spots carefully, not trying to  

389
00:33:55,520 --> 00:34:01,600
reinvent the wheel, not trying to focus on places, 
and maybe where the best foundation models are  

390
00:34:01,600 --> 00:34:05,520
excellent, but instead kind of focusing on their 
weaknesses, and how you can complement them.

391
00:34:05,520 --> 00:34:08,000
I think this is going to be surprising 
to a lot of people hearing that you have  

392
00:34:08,000 --> 00:34:12,160
your own models. When people talk about 
Cursor and all the folks in the space,  

393
00:34:12,160 --> 00:34:17,440
they would kind of call them GPT wrappers, they're 
just sitting on top of ChatGPT or Sonnet. What  

394
00:34:17,440 --> 00:34:21,760
you're saying is that you have your own models, 
talk about just the stack behind the scenes.

395
00:34:21,760 --> 00:34:27,920
Yeah, of course. So we definitely use the biggest 
foundation models a bunch of different ways,  

396
00:34:27,920 --> 00:34:32,080
they're really important components of bringing 
the Cursor experience to people. The places where  

397
00:34:32,080 --> 00:34:38,480
we use our own models, so sometimes it's to 
survey a use case that a foundation model  

398
00:34:38,480 --> 00:34:44,080
wouldn't be able to serve at all for cost or 
speed reasons. And so one example of that is  

399
00:34:44,880 --> 00:34:50,560
the autocomplete side of things. And so this 
can be a little bit tricky for people who don't  

400
00:34:50,560 --> 00:34:57,920
code to understand, but code is this weird form 
of work, where sometimes, really, the next 5,  

401
00:34:57,920 --> 00:35:02,640
10, 20, 30 minutes of your work is entirely 
predictable from looking over your shoulder. 

402
00:35:02,640 --> 00:35:09,600
And I would contrast this with writing. So 
writing, lots of people are familiar with  

403
00:35:09,600 --> 00:35:13,680
Gmail's autocomplete, and the different forms 
of autocomplete that show up when you're trying  

404
00:35:13,680 --> 00:35:18,000
to post text messages, or emails, or things like 
that. They can only be so helpful, because often,  

405
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:21,040
it's just really not clear what you're going 
to be writing just by looking at what you've  

406
00:35:21,040 --> 00:35:25,200
written before. But in code sometimes, 
when you edit a part of a code base,  

407
00:35:25,200 --> 00:35:28,800
you're going to need to change things, and in 
other parts of code base, and it's entirely  

408
00:35:28,800 --> 00:35:34,220
clear how you're going to need to change things.
So one core part of Cursor is this really suit  

409
00:35:34,220 --> 00:35:38,080
to autocomplete experience, where you predict the 
next set of that you're going to be doing across  

410
00:35:38,080 --> 00:35:44,880
multiple files, across multiple places within a 
file. And making models good at that use case,  

411
00:35:44,880 --> 00:35:48,560
one, there's a speed component of, those models 
need to be really fast, they need to give you  

412
00:35:48,560 --> 00:35:53,920
a completion within 300 milliseconds. There's 
also this cost component of, we're running tons,  

413
00:35:53,920 --> 00:35:58,160
and tons, and tons of molecules, every keystroke, 
we need to be changing our prediction for what  

414
00:35:58,160 --> 00:36:02,640
you're going to do next. And then it's also 
this really specialty use case of, you need  

415
00:36:02,640 --> 00:36:07,440
models that are really good, not at completing 
the next token, just a generic tech sequence,  

416
00:36:07,440 --> 00:36:12,240
but are really good at autocompleting a series 
of diffs, looking at what's changed within a code  

417
00:36:12,240 --> 00:36:16,160
base, and then creating the next set of things 
that are going to change, both deleted and added  

418
00:36:16,160 --> 00:36:22,960
and all of that, and we found a ton of success 
in training models specifically for that task. 

419
00:36:22,960 --> 00:36:26,960
So that's a place where no foundation models 
are involved, it's kind of our own thing. We  

420
00:36:26,960 --> 00:36:32,720
don't have a lot of labeling or branding about 
this in the app, power is a very core part of  

421
00:36:32,720 --> 00:36:39,200
Cursor. And then another set of places where a 
user own models are to help things like Sonnet,  

422
00:36:39,200 --> 00:36:44,560
or Gemini, or GPT, and those sit both 
on the inputs of those big models,  

423
00:36:44,560 --> 00:36:49,280
and on the output. On the input side of things, 
those models are searching throughout a code base,  

424
00:36:49,280 --> 00:36:54,320
try to figure out the parts of a code base to 
show to one of these big models. You can kind  

425
00:36:54,320 --> 00:36:59,920
of think about this as a mini Google search that's 
specifically built for finding the relevant parts  

426
00:36:59,920 --> 00:37:04,560
of the code base to show one of these big models.
And then on the output side of things,  

427
00:37:04,560 --> 00:37:09,400
we take the sketches of the changes that these 
models are suggesting, you make with that code  

428
00:37:09,400 --> 00:37:14,640
base. And then we have models that then fill 
in the details of, the high level thinking  

429
00:37:14,640 --> 00:37:18,400
is done by the smartest models, they spend 
a few tokens on doing that, and then these  

430
00:37:18,400 --> 00:37:24,160
smaller specialty incredibly fast models, coupled 
with some inference tricks, then take those high  

431
00:37:24,160 --> 00:37:29,120
level changes and turn them actually into full 
code diffs. And so it's been super helpful for  

432
00:37:29,120 --> 00:37:34,320
pushing on quality in places where you need a 
specialty task, and it's been super helpful for  

433
00:37:34,320 --> 00:37:39,600
pushing on speed, which is such an important 
dimension of product quality for us too.

434
00:37:39,600 --> 00:37:42,560
This is so interesting. I just 
had Kevin Weil on the podcast,  

435
00:37:42,560 --> 00:37:46,712
CPO of OpenAI, and he calls this the 
ensemble of models, that's the same way-

436
00:37:46,712 --> 00:37:46,716
Yes.

437
00:37:46,716 --> 00:37:50,960
... they work, to use the best feature of each 
one, and to your point, the cost advantages  

438
00:37:50,960 --> 00:37:56,800
of using cheaper models. These other models, 
are they based on Llama and things like that,  

439
00:37:56,800 --> 00:38:00,240
just open source models that 
you guys plug into and build on?

440
00:38:00,240 --> 00:38:05,600
Yeah. So again, we try to be very pragmatic 
about the place that we're going to do this work,  

441
00:38:05,600 --> 00:38:11,440
and we don't want to reinvent the wheel. And so 
starting from the very best pre-trained models  

442
00:38:11,440 --> 00:38:18,400
that exist out there, often open source ones, 
sometimes in collaboration with these big model  

443
00:38:18,400 --> 00:38:22,400
providers that don't share their weights out into 
the world, because the thing we care about last  

444
00:38:22,400 --> 00:38:31,120
is the ability to read line by line, the matrix of 
weights that then go to give you a certain output.  

445
00:38:31,760 --> 00:38:38,000
We just care about the ability to train these 
things, to post-train them. And so by and large,  

446
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:42,640
yes, open source models, sometimes working with 
the closed source providers too to tune things.

447
00:38:42,640 --> 00:38:46,880
This leads to a discussion that a lot of AI 
founders always think about and investors,  

448
00:38:46,880 --> 00:38:53,520
which is moats, and defensibility in AI. 
So it feels like one is custom models,  

449
00:38:53,520 --> 00:38:58,640
is a moat in the space. How do you just think 
about long-term defensibility in the space,  

450
00:38:58,640 --> 00:39:03,280
knowing there's other folks, as you said, 
launching constantly trying to eat your lunch?

451
00:39:03,280 --> 00:39:14,960
I think that there are ways to build in inertia 
and traditional moats, but I think by and large,  

452
00:39:14,960 --> 00:39:21,120
we're in a space where it is incumbent on us 
to continue to try to build the best thing,  

453
00:39:21,120 --> 00:39:28,400
and everyone in this industry. And I truly 
just think that the ceiling is so high that  

454
00:39:28,400 --> 00:39:36,960
no matter what entrenchment you build, you can 
be leapfrogged. And I think that this resembles  

455
00:39:36,960 --> 00:39:42,720
markets that are maybe a little bit different from 
normal software markets, normal enterprise markets  

456
00:39:42,720 --> 00:39:49,280
of the past. I think one that comes to mind is the 
market for search engines at the end of 1999, or  

457
00:39:49,280 --> 00:39:54,240
at the end of the '90s and beginning of the 2000s. 
I think another market that comes to mind that  

458
00:39:54,240 --> 00:39:59,760
resembles this market in many ways, it's actually 
just the development of the peripheral computer  

459
00:39:59,760 --> 00:40:06,800
and many computers in the '70s, '80s, '90s.
And I think that, yes, in each of those markets,  

460
00:40:06,800 --> 00:40:12,560
the ceiling was incredibly high, it was possible 
to swish. You could keep getting value for the  

461
00:40:12,560 --> 00:40:16,880
incremental hour of a smart person's time, the 
incremental R&D dollar for a really long time,  

462
00:40:16,880 --> 00:40:22,400
you wouldn't run out of useful things to 
build. And then in search in particular,  

463
00:40:22,400 --> 00:40:28,000
not on the computer case, adding distribution was 
helpful for making the product better too, in that  

464
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:33,440
you could tune the algorithms, you could tune the 
learning based off of the data and the feedback  

465
00:40:33,440 --> 00:40:38,960
you're getting from users. And I think that all of 
those dynamics exist in our market too. And so I  

466
00:40:38,960 --> 00:40:45,120
think maybe the sad truth for people like us, but 
then the amazing truth for the world is, I think  

467
00:40:45,120 --> 00:40:50,160
that there are many leapfrogs that exist, there's 
more useful things to build. We're a long way away  

468
00:40:50,160 --> 00:40:55,200
from where we can compete in 5, 10 years, and 
it's incumbent in our state to keep that going.

469
00:40:55,200 --> 00:40:59,040
So what I'm hearing, this sounds like a 
lot more like a consumer sort of moat,  

470
00:40:59,040 --> 00:41:02,080
where it's just, be the best thing 
consistently so that people stick with  

471
00:41:02,080 --> 00:41:06,560
you versus creating lock-in and things like 
that, where they're just... Like Salesforce,  

472
00:41:06,560 --> 00:41:10,000
where it's just contracts with the entire 
company, and you have to use this product.

473
00:41:10,000 --> 00:41:12,880
Yeah. I think the important thing to note is,  

474
00:41:13,600 --> 00:41:17,840
if you're in a space where you run out 
of useful things to do very quickly,  

475
00:41:17,840 --> 00:41:24,320
then that's not a great situation to be in. But 
if you're in a place where big investments, and  

476
00:41:26,160 --> 00:41:30,240
having more and more great people working 
on the right path can keep giving you value,  

477
00:41:30,240 --> 00:41:37,120
then you can get these economies of scale of R&D, 
and you can deeply work on the technology in the  

478
00:41:37,120 --> 00:41:43,040
right direction, and get to a place where that is 
defensible. But yes, it is... I think there's a  

479
00:41:43,040 --> 00:41:48,000
consumer-like tendency to it, and I really think 
it's just about building the best thing possible.

480
00:41:48,000 --> 00:41:50,320
Do you think in the future there's 
one winner in this space, or do you  

481
00:41:50,320 --> 00:41:53,680
think it's going to be a world of 
a number of products like this?

482
00:41:53,680 --> 00:42:02,800
I think the market is just so very big. You asked 
about the IDE thing early on, and one thing that  

483
00:42:02,800 --> 00:42:08,880
I think a trip of some people that were thinking 
about the space is, they looked at the IDE market  

484
00:42:08,880 --> 00:42:17,040
of the past 10 years, and they said, "Who's 
making money off of the editors?" It's this  

485
00:42:17,040 --> 00:42:21,200
super fragmented space where everyone kind of 
has their own thing, with their own figuration,  

486
00:42:21,200 --> 00:42:27,920
and there's one company that actually 
makes money off making great editors,  

487
00:42:27,920 --> 00:42:34,560
but that company is only so big. And then the 
conclusion was, it was going to look like that  

488
00:42:34,560 --> 00:42:39,440
in the future. And I think that the thing 
that people missed was that there was only  

489
00:42:39,440 --> 00:42:45,600
so much you could do building an editor in 
the 2010s for coders, and the company that  

490
00:42:45,600 --> 00:42:50,160
made money off of editors was doing things like 
making it easy to navigate around a code base,  

491
00:42:50,160 --> 00:42:56,320
and doing some error checking and type checking 
for things, and having good debugging tools. 

492
00:42:56,960 --> 00:43:02,320
Which were all very useful, but I think that 
the set of things you can build for programmers,  

493
00:43:02,320 --> 00:43:06,160
I think the set of things you can build for 
knowledge workers in many different areas just  

494
00:43:06,160 --> 00:43:12,960
goes very far and very deep. The problem in front 
of all of us is the automation of a lot of busy  

495
00:43:12,960 --> 00:43:17,280
work and knowledge work, and really changing all 
the areas of knowledge work in front of us to be  

496
00:43:17,280 --> 00:43:22,160
much higher level and more productive.
So that was a long-winded way to say,  

497
00:43:22,160 --> 00:43:25,680
I think the market's really, really big that 
we're in. I think it's much bigger than people  

498
00:43:25,680 --> 00:43:32,000
have realized than the other building tools for 
developers in the past. And I think that there  

499
00:43:32,000 --> 00:43:36,480
will be a bunch of different solutions. I think 
that there will be one company, to be determined  

500
00:43:36,480 --> 00:43:42,320
if it's going to be us, but I do think that there 
will be one company that builds the general tool  

501
00:43:42,320 --> 00:43:46,640
that builds almost all the world's software, 
and that will be a very, very generationally  

502
00:43:46,640 --> 00:43:51,520
big business. But I think that there will be 
kind of niches you can occupy in doing something  

503
00:43:51,520 --> 00:43:55,040
for a particular segment of the market, or for a 
very particular part of the software development  

504
00:43:55,040 --> 00:44:00,000
life cycle. But the general programming shifts 
from just writing formal programming languages  

505
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:04,560
to something way higher level. This is 
the application you purchase and use to  

506
00:44:04,560 --> 00:44:11,040
do that. I think that there will be generally one 
winner there, and it will be a very big business.

507
00:44:11,040 --> 00:44:18,240
Juicy. Along those lines, it's interesting 
that Microsoft was actually at the center of  

508
00:44:18,240 --> 00:44:24,160
this first, with an amazing product, amazing 
distribution, Copilot you said was the thing  

509
00:44:24,160 --> 00:44:28,720
that got you over the hump of, "Wow, there could 
be something really big here." And it doesn't  

510
00:44:28,720 --> 00:44:34,160
feel like they're winning, it feels like they're 
falling behind. What do you think happened there?

511
00:44:34,160 --> 00:44:42,240
I think that there are specific historical reasons 
why Copilot might not have lived up... So far have  

512
00:44:43,280 --> 00:44:45,920
lived up to the expectations that some 
people have for it, and then I think that  

513
00:44:45,920 --> 00:44:51,120
there are structural reasons. I think the 
structural reason is... And to be clear,  

514
00:44:51,120 --> 00:44:57,760
Microsoft, in the Copilot case, obviously a 
big inspiration for our work, and in general,  

515
00:44:57,760 --> 00:45:02,400
I think they do lots of awesome things, 
and we're users of many Microsoft products,  

516
00:45:04,080 --> 00:45:10,000
but I think that this is a market that's 
not super friendly to incumbents, in that  

517
00:45:11,280 --> 00:45:14,960
a market that's friendly to incumbents might 
be one where there's only so much to do,  

518
00:45:14,960 --> 00:45:19,040
it kind of gets commoditized fairly quickly, 
and you can bundle that in with other products,  

519
00:45:19,040 --> 00:45:26,800
and where the ROI between different products 
is quite small. And in that case, perhaps it  

520
00:45:26,800 --> 00:45:29,440
doesn't make sense to buy the innovative 
solution, it makes sense to just kind of  

521
00:45:29,440 --> 00:45:34,400
buy the thing that's bundled in with other stuff.
Another market that might be particularly helpful  

522
00:45:34,400 --> 00:45:40,480
for incumbents is one where there's... From 
the get-go, you have your stuff in one place,  

523
00:45:40,480 --> 00:45:45,760
and it's really, really excruciatingly hard to 
switch, and for better or for worse. I think in  

524
00:45:45,760 --> 00:45:49,840
our case, you can try out different tools, and you 
can decide which product you think is better. And  

525
00:45:49,840 --> 00:45:55,040
so that's not super friendly to incumbents, and 
that's more friendly to whoever you think is going  

526
00:45:55,040 --> 00:46:00,080
to have the most innovative product. And then the 
specific historical reasons, as I understand them  

527
00:46:00,080 --> 00:46:05,360
are the group of people that worked on the 
first version of Copilot have, by and large,  

528
00:46:05,360 --> 00:46:10,080
gone on to do other things at other places. I 
think it's been a little hard to coordinate among  

529
00:46:10,080 --> 00:46:14,800
all the different departments and parties that 
might be involved in making something like this.

530
00:46:14,800 --> 00:46:19,600
I want to come back to Cursor. A question I like 
to ask everyone that's building a tool like this,  

531
00:46:19,600 --> 00:46:25,120
if you could sit next to every new user that uses 
Cursor for the first time, just whisper a couple  

532
00:46:25,120 --> 00:46:32,320
tips in their ear to be more successful, most 
successful with Cursor, what would be 1 or 2 tips?

533
00:46:32,320 --> 00:46:37,360
I think right now, and we'd want to fix this at 
a product level, a lot of being successful with  

534
00:46:37,360 --> 00:46:43,680
Cursor is kind of having a taste for what 
the models can do, both what complexity of  

535
00:46:43,680 --> 00:46:51,760
a task they can handle, and how much you need to 
specify things to that model, but having a taste  

536
00:46:51,760 --> 00:46:57,200
for the quality of the model, and where its gaps 
exist, and what it can do and what it can't. And  

537
00:46:57,200 --> 00:47:02,640
right now, we don't do a good job in the 
product of educating people around that,  

538
00:47:02,640 --> 00:47:06,000
and maybe giving people some swim 
lanes, giving people some guidelines. 

539
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:15,520
But to develop that taste, would give two tips. 
So one is, as mentioned before, would bias less  

540
00:47:15,520 --> 00:47:24,160
toward, trying in one go to tell the model, "Hey, 
here's exactly what I want you to do." Then seeing  

541
00:47:24,160 --> 00:47:28,320
the output, and then either being disappointed or 
accepting the entire thing for an entire big task.  

542
00:47:28,320 --> 00:47:32,800
Instead what I would do is I would chop things up 
into bits, and you can spend basically the same  

543
00:47:32,800 --> 00:47:37,360
amount of time specifying things overall, but 
chopped up more. So you're specifying a little  

544
00:47:37,360 --> 00:47:39,440
bit, you're getting a little bit of work, 
you're specifying a little bit, getting a  

545
00:47:39,440 --> 00:47:44,080
little bit of work, and not doing as much the, 
"Let's write a giant thing telling the model  

546
00:47:44,080 --> 00:47:48,640
exactly what to do." I think that will be a 
little bit of a recipe for disaster right now. 

547
00:47:48,640 --> 00:47:53,440
And so biasing toward chopping things up. 
At the same time, and it might make sense  

548
00:47:53,440 --> 00:47:58,720
to do this on a side project and not on your 
professional work, I would encourage people to,  

549
00:47:58,720 --> 00:48:05,360
especially developers who are used to 
existing workflows for building software,  

550
00:48:05,360 --> 00:48:11,600
I would encourage people to explicitly try to fall 
on their face, and try to discover the limits of  

551
00:48:11,600 --> 00:48:18,720
what these models can do by being ambitious in 
a safe environment, like perhaps a side project,  

552
00:48:18,720 --> 00:48:24,000
and trying to kind of go around town, use AI 
to the fullest. Because a lot of the time,  

553
00:48:24,000 --> 00:48:31,280
we run into people who haven't given the AI yet a 
fair shake, and are underestimating its abilities.  

554
00:48:31,280 --> 00:48:35,440
So generally biasing towards chopping things 
up and making things smaller, but to discover  

555
00:48:35,440 --> 00:48:40,080
the limits of what you can do there, explicitly 
just try to go for broke in a safe environment,  

556
00:48:40,080 --> 00:48:45,360
and get a taste for... You might be surprised in 
some of the places where the model doesn't break.

557
00:48:45,360 --> 00:48:50,240
What I'm essentially hearing is build 
a gut feeling of what the model can do,  

558
00:48:50,240 --> 00:48:55,840
and how far it can take an idea versus 
just kind of guiding it along. And I  

559
00:48:55,840 --> 00:48:59,200
bet that you need to rebuild this gut 
every time there's a new model launch,  

560
00:48:59,200 --> 00:49:04,240
when it's on... I don't know, 4.0 comes out, you 
have to do this again. Is that generally right?

561
00:49:04,240 --> 00:49:12,960
Yes. For the past few years, it hasn't been 
as big as I think the first experience people  

562
00:49:12,960 --> 00:49:18,240
have had with some of these big models. 
This is also a problem we would hope to  

563
00:49:18,240 --> 00:49:22,240
solve much better just for users, and 
take the burden off of them. But each  

564
00:49:22,240 --> 00:49:26,240
of these things have slightly different 
quirks and different personalities.

565
00:49:26,240 --> 00:49:30,000
Along these lines, something that people 
are always debating tools like Cursor,  

566
00:49:30,000 --> 00:49:35,120
are they more helpful to junior engineers, or 
are they more helpful to senior engineers? Do  

567
00:49:35,120 --> 00:49:37,920
they make senior engineers 10X better? 
Do they make junior engineers more like  

568
00:49:37,920 --> 00:49:43,440
senior engineers? Who do you think 
benefits most today from Cursor?

569
00:49:43,440 --> 00:49:49,200
I think across the board. Both of these 
cohorts benefit in big ways. It's a little  

570
00:49:49,200 --> 00:49:54,880
hard to say on the relative ranking. I will 
say, they fall into different anti-patterns.  

571
00:49:55,760 --> 00:50:02,720
The junior engineers we see going a little 
too wholesale, relying on AI for everything,  

572
00:50:02,720 --> 00:50:08,240
and we're not yet in a place where you can kind 
of do that end-to-end on a professional tool,  

573
00:50:08,240 --> 00:50:13,280
working with tens, hundreds of other people 
within a long-lived code base. And then the  

574
00:50:13,280 --> 00:50:20,640
senior engineers... For many folks, it's not 
true for all, and we actually often... One of  

575
00:50:20,640 --> 00:50:24,000
the ways these tools are adopted is, there's 
developer experience teams within companies,  

576
00:50:24,000 --> 00:50:30,000
often those are staffed by incredibly senior 
people, because often, those are people who  

577
00:50:30,000 --> 00:50:33,440
are building tools to make the rest of the 
engineers within an organization more productive. 

578
00:50:33,440 --> 00:50:42,560
And we've seen some very, very boundary pushing 
kind of... We've seen people who are on the front  

579
00:50:42,560 --> 00:50:46,800
lines of really trying to adopt the technology as 
much as possible there. But by and large, I would  

580
00:50:46,800 --> 00:50:53,760
say on average, as a group, the senior engineers 
underrate what AI can do for them, and stick to  

581
00:50:53,760 --> 00:50:58,000
their existing workflows. And so the relative 
ranking is a little hard, I think they fall  

582
00:50:58,000 --> 00:51:04,080
into different anti-patterns, but they both, by 
and large, yet get big benefits with these tools.

583
00:51:04,080 --> 00:51:08,160
That makes absolute sense. I love 
that it's two ends of the spectrum,  

584
00:51:08,160 --> 00:51:15,520
expect too much, don't expect enough. 
It's like the three bears allegory.

585
00:51:15,520 --> 00:51:16,400
Yeah.

586
00:51:16,400 --> 00:51:17,680
Yeah. Okay.

587
00:51:18,240 --> 00:51:24,480
Yeah. Maybe the sort of senior, 
but not staff, right in the middle.

588
00:51:24,480 --> 00:51:30,160
Interesting. Okay. Just a couple more questions. 
What's something that you wish you knew before  

